"Kiambi D.K., Newbury H.J., Maxted N., Ford-Lloyd B.V.","Molecular genetic variation in the African wild rice Oryza longistaminata A. Chev. et Roehr. and its association with environmental variables",2008,"African Journal of Biotechnology","7","10",,"1446","1460",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-44649177720&partnerID=40&md5=205d8120a1f0738aae29ea2395d5cb47","International Crops Research Institute for the Semi-Arid Tropics (ICRISAT), P.O. Box 30709-00100, Nairobi, Kenya; School of Biosciences, University of Birmingham, Edgbaston, Birmingham B15 2TT, United Kingdom","Kiambi, D.K., International Crops Research Institute for the Semi-Arid Tropics (ICRISAT), P.O. Box 30709-00100, Nairobi, Kenya; Newbury, H.J., School of Biosciences, University of Birmingham, Edgbaston, Birmingham B15 2TT, United Kingdom; Maxted, N., School of Biosciences, University of Birmingham, Edgbaston, Birmingham B15 2TT, United Kingdom; Ford-Lloyd, B.V., School of Biosciences, University of Birmingham, Edgbaston, Birmingham B15 2TT, United Kingdom","Molecular markers, complemented by appropriate Geographical Information System (GIS) software packages are powerful tools in mapping the geographical distribution of genetic variation and assessing its relationship with environmental variables. The objective of the study was therefore to investigate the relationship between genetic diversity and eco-geographic variables using Oryza longistaminata as a case study. The methodology used was a novel technique that combined hierarchical cluster analysis of both molecular diversity generated using Amplified Fragment Length Polymorphism (AFLP) and climate data available in a GIS software. The study clearly established that there is a close relationship between genetic diversity and eco-geographic variables. The study also revealed that genetic diversity is a function of annual rainfall, and peak diversity occurs in intermediate rainfall areas reflecting the 'curvilinear theory' of clinal relationship between the level of genetic diversity and rainfall. The clear association of genetic diversity with rainfall allows the extrapolation of the potential impacts of global warming on diversity when empirical data on predicted climate models, particularly rainfall, are available. This knowledge would therefore be useful in the development of conservation measures to mitigate the effects of genetic erosion through climate change. © 2008 Academic Journals.","AFLP; Eco-geographical distribution; Environmental variables; Genetic variation; GIS; Molecular diversity","molecular marker; rain; algorithm; amplified fragment length polymorphism; article; climate; climate change; cluster analysis; computer program; ecology; environmental factor; genetic correlation; genetic erosion; genetic variability; genotype environment interaction; geographic distribution; geographic information system; geography; greenhouse effect; nonhuman; Oryza longistaminata; prediction; rice; Oryza barthii; Oryza longistaminata",,,,,,"Allard, R.W., Kahler, A.L., Allozyme polymorphism in plant populations (1971) Stadler Symposium Univiversity of Missouri, 3, pp. 9-24; Bezançon, G., Bozza, J.L., Second, G., Variability of Oryza longistaminata and the sativa complex in Africa. Ecology and evolutive aspects (1977) IRAT-ORSTORM meeting on African rice species, pp. 47-55. , Institute de Recherche Agronomique Tropicales-Office de la Recherche Scientifique et technique de Outre Mer, Paris; Brown, A.H.D., Weir, B.S., Measuring genetic variability in plant populations (1983) Isozymes in plant genetics and breeding, , Tanksley SD, Orton TJ, editors, Elsevier Science Publishers, B. V. Amsterdam; Brown, J.H., Lomolino, M.V., (1998) Biogeography, , Sinauer Associates, Inc. USA; Christiansen, F.B., Frydenberg, O., Geographical patterns of four polymorphisms in Zoarces viviparous as evidence of selection (1974) Genetics, 77, pp. 765-770; Dawson, I.K., Simons, A.J., Waugh, R., Powell, W., Diversity and ge